\begin_body

\begin_layout Section
Argument 2
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I have two arguments against using standardized alpha for standardized test
 items.
 First, you should not standardize test items.
 Second, even if you decide to standardize test items, please avoid standardized
 alpha and use a suitably modified congeneric reliability instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My point of departure is the following quote of Osburn (p.
 348):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
enquote{However, it is important to note that the true reliability of a
 measure is the same for both standardized and unstandardized observed scores.}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will argue against this.
 The purpose of a reliability coefficient is, among other things, to be
 used to correct correlations for attenuation.
 In order for this to be possible, the reliability has to be the 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 between the predicted value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 and the true 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 will change on the population level when you use standardized scores, as
 I will explain soon.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
How you interpret 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 changes when you stop viewing it as an approximation to the congeneric
 reliability 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 to an approximation to the standardized reliability 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

.
 For instance, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}=\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 will be true in a more general setting now, not only for parallel models
 (as we will see, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}=\omega$
\end_inset

 under the parallel model).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So the question is not only if you believe in the parallel model, but if
 (a) if you actually want to standardize, and (b) if you can believe in
 the new assumptions about the model implied by your usage of the standardized
 congeneric reliability.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For question (a), I will argue against standardizing your variables, at
 least in the usual sense.
 For question (b), I will argue you should not use 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 even if you choose to standardize your variables, but rather the standardized
 congeneric reliability instead.
 Before I can start expanding on these arguments, I will have to explain
 the concept of reliability and why you do not want to approximate 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 when you standardize your scores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let me explain what it means to standardize scores in this setting.
 Assume the congeneric model with 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 items.
 Suppose you know the vector of loadings 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and all the error variances 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 You observe the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in\mathbb{R}^{k}$
\end_inset

 and want to use to the knowledge about 
\begin_inset Formula $X,\lambda$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 to predict the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The easiest to way is to predict 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is the sum score, or 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The mean squared error of this prediction is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\left(Z-\widehat{Z}\right)^{2}\right]=E\left[\left(Z-\sum\lambda Z+\Psi^{1/2}\epsilon\right)^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using standardized scores is different.
 Instead of using the sum score, you use a linear function of 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

, with weights equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\widehat{Z}_{(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}X_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I will now argue you are never justified to use 
\begin_inset Formula $w=(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 Using some 
\begin_inset Formula $w\ne1$
\end_inset

 seems reasonable, for you would not want items with large variance to overshado
w all the other contributions to 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{k}X_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 But there is something strange about this particular 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

.
 Wouldn't it be just as sensible to use 
\begin_inset Formula $w=\sigma_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

? Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}$
\end_inset

 seems wrong, because you want items with large loadings to have a large
 influece on your prediction of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 But while we are at it, why not just use the optimal weights, yielding
 coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and the Thurstone factor scores instead of the standardized alpha and standardi
zed sum scores?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What we need is a way to compare weights.
 Before we start on this, recall that 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 is forced to have variance 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 in the congeneric model.
 In this cae, the sum score 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{k}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 does not make sense a predictor of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

, as it does not take the scale into account.
 The scale can be ignored when using only sum scores, but cannot be ignored
 when we compare sum scores to other kinds of scores.
 Instead of dealing with sum scores directly, we will deal with scores of
 the type
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{0}\sum_{i=1}^{k}X_{i},
\]

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
w_{0} & = & \argmin_{w\in\mathbb{R}}E\left[\left(Z-w\sum_{i=1}^{k}X_{i}\right)^{2}\right].\nonumber \\
 & = & \overline{\lambda^{2}}/\left(k\overline{\lambda}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}}\right)\label{eq:w0}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

See the appendix page [[ref]] for a proof for the argmin.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the mean squared errors
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textsc{MSE}=E\left[\left(Z-EZ\right)\right]=\Var Z=1,
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Var Z=1$
\end_inset

 by assumption, and the mean squared error of
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\textsc{MSE}\left(\widehat{Z}\right)=E\left[\left(Z-\widehat{Z}\right)^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}$
\end_inset

-reliability as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right) & =1-\frac{\textsc{MSE}\left(\widehat{Z}\right)}{\textsc{MSE}}= & 1-\textsc{MSE}\left(\widehat{Z}\right)\label{eq:Z-reliability}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By the law of total variance, 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\textsc{MSE}\left(\widehat{Z}\right)\leq1$
\end_inset

, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)\leq1$
\end_inset

 too.
 The definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega(\widehat{Z})$
\end_inset

 is analagous to that of 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

, and it shares most of its properties.
 I will explore the connection between reliabiltiy coefficients and 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{2}$
\end_inset

 further in a future paper.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:Z-reliabiltiy"

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}=\sum_{i=1}^{k}w_{i}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 be a linear predictor of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}=w_{0}\sum_{i=1}^{k}X_{i}$
\end_inset

 is the sum score, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}$
\end_inset

-reliability 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)$
\end_inset

 equals the congeneric reliability,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)=\omega=\frac{k\overline{\lambda}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}}}{k\overline{\lambda}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}}+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 are the 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{2}$
\end_inset

-optimal weights, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is the solution to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\argmin_{w}\textsc{MSE}\left(\widehat{Z}\right)=E\left[\left(Z-\sum_{i=1}^{k}w_{i}X_{i}\right)^{2}\right]
\]

\end_inset

then the 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}$
\end_inset

-reliability 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)$
\end_inset

 equals coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)=\omega_{H}=\frac{k\overline{\lambda^{2}\sigma^{-2}}}{k\overline{\lambda^{2}\sigma^{-2}}+1}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $w=w_{0}(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)=\frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1}}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1}}+1}\label{eq:Standardized reliability}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
If 
\begin_inset Formula $w=w_{0}\sigma_{i}^{-1}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)=\frac{k\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}+1}\label{eq:Sigma-standardized reliability}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
(Please write down the proof, please.) (iii) Consider the modified model
 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}=X\lambda_{i}(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}+\epsilon$
\end_inset

, which is congeneric with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{\star}=\lambda/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{\star}=\sigma/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 By [[ref congeneric]], 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right) & = & \frac{k\overline{\lambda^{\star}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda^{\star}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{\star2}}}\\
 & = & \frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

(iv) This one is similar to (ii).
 Just use the modified model 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}=X\lambda\sigma^{-1}+\epsilon$
\end_inset

, which is congeneric with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{\star}=\lambda/\sigma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{\star}=1$
\end_inset

.
 By [[ref congeneric]],
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right) & = & \frac{k\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}+1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The predicted values 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}$
\end_inset

 are factor scores, and the reliabiltiy coefficients in Propositions 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Z-reliabiltiy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are to the implied factor score.
 For coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

, the factor scores are the Thurstone regressions scores, for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 the appropriately weighted sum scores, and for 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 the ordinary sum score.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
No one would use the standardized reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Standardized reliability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 or the sigma reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Sigma-standardized reliability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}^{2}=\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 The following Theorem exposes a basic fact about these three reliability
 coefficients:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "prop:Properties of three"

\end_inset

 Assume the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent model, i.e.
 the congeneric model with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\lambda>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 but possibly different 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

s.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 be the congeneric reliability, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 the standardized reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Standardized reliability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 the sigma reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Sigma-standardized reliability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{H}$
\end_inset

 coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{h}\geq\omega_{\sigma}\geq\omega_{s}\geq\omega,
\]

\end_inset

with all inequalities strict unless 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma\geq0$
\end_inset

 or all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Each reliability is on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $a/(a+1)$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $a>0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $a/(a+1)\geq b(b+1)$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $a>b$
\end_inset

.
 Let's take on 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{h}\geq\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 first, which happens iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\lambda^{2}\sigma^{-2}}\geq\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Expand it and use Chebyshev's inequality to see 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{h}\geq\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 is true with equality only when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma\geq0$
\end_inset

 or all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let's take on 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}>\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 first.
 That is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\lambda^{2}\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{2}\geq k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1}}
\]

\end_inset

this is equivalent to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\geq\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}\right]^{2}\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{-2}
\]

\end_inset

Divide boths sides with 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}/\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a weighted mean with 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}$
\end_inset

 decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 By Lemma [[ref]], 
\begin_inset Formula $m\leq\overline{\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

, hence 
\series bold
???????
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
m
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Now look at 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}>\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 first.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1}}\geq k\overline{\lambda}^{2}/\overline{\sigma^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\overline{\sigma^{2}}\geq\overline{\sigma^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1}}
\]

\end_inset

or
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}\right]^{2}\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}\geq\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}(\lambda+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a weighted mean with 
\begin_inset Formula $w_{i}=(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}$
\end_inset

 decreasing in 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
k\left[\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}\right]^{2}\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{-1}\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}\geq\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}(\lambda+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\label{eq:inequality, omega_s > omega}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We know
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}\geq\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}(\lambda+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

from Lemma [[ref]].
 From Chebyshev's inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k\left[\frac{1}{k}\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}\right]^{2}\left[\sum_{i=1}^{k}(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}\right]^{-1}\geq1
\]

\end_inset

Plug it into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:inequality, omega_s > omega"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to get the inequality we want.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can interpret Theorem 2 as a ranking factor scores too.
 It says regression scores are better than 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

-standardized sum scores, which in turn are better than the standardized
 sum scores, which are better than the ordinary sum scores.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use the expressions of Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Z-reliabiltiy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to compare the effect of 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{Z}$
\end_inset

 on the reliability of our measurements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 uses the optimal weights, it is guarateed to be larger than the three other
 reliabilities mentioned above.
 The other three reliabilities can be in any order, but will usually follow
 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 will usually be the largest, sometimes .
 In a short simulation (
\begin_inset Formula $10^{5}$
\end_inset

 repetitions) of 
\begin_inset Formula $k=5$
\end_inset

 items with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}\sim\Exp(1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\sim\Exp(1)$
\end_inset

 idependently with 
\begin_inset Formula $i=1,\ldots,5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 was the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $0.98\%$
\end_inset

 of the time, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 largest 
\begin_inset Formula $0.02\%$
\end_inset

 of the time, but 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 was never the largest (
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}>\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 happened though).
 The congeneric 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 dominated 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $6$
\end_inset

 of 
\begin_inset Formula $10$
\end_inset

 iterations.
 You could argue this simulation study is somewhat unrealistic: In a slightly
 different simulation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}^{2}\sim N(0,1)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\sim\HalfNormal(0,1)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 was the largest 
\begin_inset Formula $0.92\%$
\end_inset

 of the time and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}>\omega$
\end_inset

 a nice 
\begin_inset Formula $70\%$
\end_inset

 of the time.
 Again, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 was never the largest, which suggest it cannot be larger than both 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 at the same time.
 The take-away from these two simulation studies is that 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 generally does better than 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, while it is hard to predict the winner among 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
My second argument against 
\begin_inset Formula $(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1}$
\end_inset

 follows Falk.
 The assumptions of a 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent model are hard to justify to begin with, and unlikely to be
 true.
 The standardized coefficient alpha equals the congeneric reliability for
 standardized variable (i.e 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega\left(\widehat{Z}\right)$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:Standardized reliability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Z-reliabiltiy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) only when the modified model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{i}^{\star}=\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2}}}Z+\frac{\sigma_{i}}{\sqrt{\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2}}}\epsilon_{i}\:i=1,\ldots,k
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent.
 This occurs if and only if each 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}/(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})=\lambda^{\star}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Of course, this would be an exceptional conincidence.
 To avoid this crazy assumption, use structural equation modeling to estimate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i},\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

, and plug them into the formula for the congeneric reliability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This observation also counters a possible, but wrong, interpretation of
 Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Properties of three"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Properties of three"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 states 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}>\omega$
\end_inset

 under the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent model.
 Second, coefficient alpha equals 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 under the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent model.
 Then it seems reasonable to use standardized alpha, doesn't it? After all,
 standardized alpha can be calculated from the covariance matrix alone,
 and does not require any model assumptions But this is wrong! For as mentionion
ed, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}=\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 only when 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}/(\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})=\lambda$
\end_inset

.
 Otherwise, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}<\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 by Propositon 1.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

, an alpha for 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Both coefficient alpha and standardized alpha are simple functions of the
 covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

.
 The reliability coefficients in Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Z-reliabiltiy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 are not simple functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 except under exceptional circumstances such as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalence.
 Everything else being equal, simple solutions should be preferred over
 complex solutions, and this is a common argument for coefficient alpha
 [[ref]].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Just as 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 has 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset

, the sigma reliability 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:Sigma-standardized reliability"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 has its own 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

-coefficient.
 The covariance matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

 under the 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent model has diagonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and off-digonal elements 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{2}=\left(k-1\right)^{-1}\left(\mathbf{i}^{T}\Sigma\mathbf{i}/k-\tr\Sigma/k\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=\diag\Sigma-\lambda^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the sigma standardized matrix
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\Xi & = & \diag\sigma^{-1}\Sigma\diag\sigma^{-1},
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

and the sigma coefficient alpha as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
\alpha_{\sigma} & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(1-\frac{\tr\Xi}{\mathbf{i}^{T}\Xi\mathbf{i}}\right)\label{eq:alpha_sigma-1}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\sigma}=\omega_{\sigma}$
\end_inset

 only when
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{i}^{\star}=\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sigma_{i}}Z+\epsilon_{i}\:i=1,\ldots,k
\]

\end_inset

is 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

-equivalent.
 This happens if and only if every standardized factor loading is the same,
 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}/\sigma_{i}=\lambda^{\star}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 From Proposition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "prop:Z-reliabiltiy"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 (iii) and (ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{\sigma}=\omega_{\sigma}=\omega_{H}$
\end_inset

 in this case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You can judge for yourself what assumptions are most likely to hold.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To conclude, I have two arguments against using standardized alpha for standardi
zed test items.
 First, you should not standardize test items.
 Second, even if you decide to standardize test items, please avoid standardized
 alpha and.
 Use coefficient 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 or the sigma reliability instead.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Part
Notes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparison of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{s}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\omega_{s} & = & \frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}\\
\alpha_{s} & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}+k}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\left(\sum\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}\text{-\ensuremath{\sum\left(\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}}{\left(\sum\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}\text{-\ensuremath{\sum\left(\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}+k}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\left(\sum\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}\text{-\ensuremath{\sum\left(\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}}{\left(\sum\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}\text{-\ensuremath{\sum\left(\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}+\sum\left(\frac{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\left(\sum\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}\text{-\ensuremath{\sum\left(\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}}}{\left(\sum\frac{\lambda_{i}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}+\sum\left(\frac{\sigma_{i}^{2}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}}\right)^{2}}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\text{-}\overline{\lambda^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

This equals 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{k}{k-1}\left[k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\text{-}\overline{\lambda^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}\right] & = & k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\\
\left[k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\text{-}\overline{\lambda^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}\right] & = & \left(k-1\right)\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\\
\overline{\lambda^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})} & = & \overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a=k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c=\overline{\lambda^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}$
\end_inset

 then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\omega_{s}=\frac{a}{a+b}
\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{s}=\frac{k}{k-1}\frac{a-c}{a+b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{s}=\frac{a}{a+b}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Properties of the four reliabilities
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}=\sigma$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 the sigma reliability equals the congeneric reliability.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda\sigma^{-1}}^{2}+1}=\frac{k\overline{\lambda}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda}^{2}+\sigma^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

On the other hand, the standardized reliability is smaller:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}} & = & \frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\sigma^{2}/\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}\\
 & = & \frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\sigma^{2}/\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

When 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\lambda$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}=\lambda$
\end_inset

, the sigma reliability is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k\lambda^{2}\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{2}}{k\lambda^{2}\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{2}+1}=\frac{k\lambda^{2}}{k\lambda^{2}+1/\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and since 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{2}<\overline{\sigma}^{2}$
\end_inset

 by the harmonic mean inequality, with equality only when all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

s are equal, the sigma reliability dominates the congeneric reliability
 in this case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As for
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}} & = & \frac{k\lambda^{2}\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}{k\lambda^{2}\overline{\lambda(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}}\\
 & = & \frac{k\lambda^{2}}{k\lambda^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}/\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{s}\geq\omega$
\end_inset

 iff 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}/\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\leq\overline{\sigma}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This inequality can be proved using Theorem 2 of Sbert and Poch together
 with Chebyshev's inequality, with equality only when all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

s are equal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider 
\begin_inset Formula $1/\overline{\sigma^{-1}}^{2}\leq\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}/\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}\leq\overline{\sigma^{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When both the 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

s and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 are unequal, all are possible.
 (Provide example.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\overline{\sigma^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})}/\overline{(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2})^{-1/2}}^{2}=\frac{\sum\sigma_{i}^{2}/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})}{\sum1/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})}\frac{k\sum1/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})}{\left[\sum1/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}\right]^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Here 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k\sum1/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})}{\left[\sum1/(\lambda^{2}+\sigma_{i}^{2})^{-1/2}\right]^{2}}\geq1
\]

\end_inset

with equality iff all 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}$
\end_inset

s are equal, by Chebyshev's equality.
 By the harmonic mean inequality,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{k}\sigma_{i}^{2}w_{i}\geq\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\frac{w_{i}}{\sigma_{i}^{2}}\right)^{-1}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{k}w}{\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}w_{i}^{1/2}\right)^{2}}k\sum_{i=1}^{k}x_{i}w_{i}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Stuff
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\alpha_{s} & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(1-\frac{k}{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}+k}\right)\\
 & = & \frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}+k}\right)
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}+k}\right)=\frac{k\overline{\lambda}^{2}}{k\overline{\lambda}^{2}+\overline{\sigma^{2}}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\frac{\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}\sqrt{\sigma_{j}^{2}+\lambda_{j}^{2}}}+k}\right)=\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}+\sum\lambda_{i}^{2}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}+\sum\left(\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}=\sqrt{a}$
\end_inset

 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
 Then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum\left(\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}\right)=ak$
\end_inset

 and
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{k}{k-1}\left(\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}+ak}\right)=\frac{\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}+\sum\lambda_{i}^{2}}{\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}+ak}
\]

\end_inset

which is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{k}{k-1}\left(\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}\right) & = & \sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j}+\sum\lambda_{i}^{2}\\
\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j} & = & \left(k-1\right)\sum_{i=1}^{k}\lambda_{i}^{2}\\
\sum_{i=1}^{k}\lambda_{i}^{2}+\sum_{i\neq j}\lambda_{i}\lambda_{j} & = & k\sum_{i=1}^{k}\lambda_{i}^{2}\\
\left(\sum_{i=1}^{k}\lambda_{i}\right)^{2} & = & k\sum_{i=1}^{k}\lambda_{i}^{2}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

The solution is
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\ensuremath{\lambda_{i}=\lambda_{j}}}$
\end_inset

for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key 1: Is continuous.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key 2: Is greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma_{i}\neq\sigma_{j}$
\end_inset

 for some 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j$
\end_inset

 and all 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

s are equal
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Key 3: Is less than 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{\sqrt{\sigma_{i}^{2}+\lambda_{i}^{2}}=\sqrt{a}}$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 but some 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{i}$
\end_inset

 is different from the others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Okay, write this down and find an example.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
2\left(\frac{2\frac{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}{ab}}{2\frac{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}{ab}+2}\right) & = & \frac{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}+\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}}{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}+a^{2}+b^{2}}\\
2\left(\frac{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}}{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}+2ab}\right) & = & \frac{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}+\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}}{2\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}+a^{2}+b^{2}}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Assume 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}=1$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
2\left(\frac{2\lambda_{1}}{2\lambda_{1}+2ab}\right)=\frac{2\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{1}^{2}+1}{2\lambda_{1}+a^{2}+b^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
4\lambda_{1}\left(2\lambda_{1}+a^{2}+b^{2}\right)=\left(2\lambda_{1}+\lambda_{1}^{2}+1\right)\left(2\lambda_{1}+2ab\right)
\]

\end_inset

Now put 
\begin_inset Formula $a=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
4\lambda_{1}\left(2\lambda_{1}+5\right)=\left(\lambda+1\right)^{2}\left(2\lambda_{1}+4\right)
\]

\end_inset

This is a cubic equation with solutions in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 2,-1-\sqrt{2},\sqrt{2}-1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\lambda^{2}}{\left(\lambda^{2}+\sigma^{2}\right)+\frac{\left(1-\sigma^{2}\right)}{k}}
\]

\end_inset


